### 1. The Parsing Logic
This section handles the raw data from the Excel/CSV file. If it encounters the string `"NO SALE"` or `"N/A"`, it converts the value to `0` so the mathematical analysis can process it consistently.

```typescript
// Located in utils/dataProcessor.ts (inside parseFile function)
let rawMoh = getItem(map.mohTotal);
let mohValue = 0;

if (typeof rawMoh === 'string') {
  const normalizedMoh = rawMoh.toUpperCase().trim();
  // Check specifically for "NO SALE"
  if (normalizedMoh === 'NO SALE' || normalizedMoh === 'N/A') {
    mohValue = 0;
  } else {
    mohValue = parseFloat(rawMoh) || 0;
  }
} else {
  mohValue = Number(rawMoh) || 0;
}
```

### 2. The Business Rule Logic
This is the "gatekeeper" that decides which items appear in the Shortfalls tab. By adding `item.mohTotal > 0`, we ensure that any item with 0 months of stock (including those parsed as "NO SALE") is ignored by the alert.

```typescript
// Located in utils/dataProcessor.ts (inside analyzeInventory function)
if (item.mohTotal < 2 && item.mohTotal > 0 && item.accuracy >= 0.8) {
  // item.mohTotal > 0 is the key check that excludes "NO SALE" items
  shortfall.push({ item, risks: [RiskCategory.SHORTFALL] });
}
